{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502613"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:47:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:47:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1881"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1881"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.02,0.12,0.49,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1881"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80396"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"759"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16590"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 92-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24 hour history of generalised colicky abdominal pain and distension. Her symptoms are becoming more severe. Her medical history includes a laparotomy and colectomy ten years earlier for a carcinoma of the colon. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer abdomen is distended, but soft. Increased bowel sounds are evident. A CT scan is arranged, with the request stating \u0027abdominal pain - cause unknown.\u0027 (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adhesive-obstruction","Paralytic ileus","Obturator hernia","Femoral hernia","Large bowel obstruction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDilated loops of small bowel can clearly be seen on the scan. There is a protrusion of a knuckle of small bowel through the femoral canal - as shown by the arrow (image). The partial effacement of the femoral vein gives more proof that the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehernia is in the femoral canal\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst an obturator hernia might produce a similar clinical picture, the hernial defect is in the groin and not on the pelvic floor. Likewise, based on the patient\u0027s symptoms and history of previous abdominal surgery, adhesive-obstruction would be a reasonable diagnosis - but ruled out by the CT findings. Paralytic ileus is not associated with colicky abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this particular case, the hernia could be seen and felt quite clearly. With the current dynamics in Emergency Room assessment care, in terms of overcrowding by admitted patients and the need for more senior staff to be available for decision-making, perhaps undue pressure is placed on medical staff to provide an rapid diagnosis and onward referral. This would explain the deferment to radiological imaging rather than proper physical examination. This is a real case and it was unfortunate that, for whatever reasons, the Emergency Room staff did not do a proper physical examination. If they had done so, the CT examination would have been superfluous.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most groin hernias are identified on clinical examination and do not need a CT scan for their elucidation."],"references":["Bad T, Macha M, Mayberry J. The utility of CT scan for the diagnostic evaluation of acute abdominal pain. Am J Surg 2019.02.003.","Judkins S. ED overcrowding, under-resourcing \u201cworst in 30 years\u201d. Insight April 26th 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80396"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1881"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18638"},{"type":"media","id":"18639"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18640"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18638"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/481a7e77-54c3-4fe3-bf24-7445ac210859.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/481a7e77-54c3-4fe3-bf24-7445ac210859.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":512,"height":306}},{"type":"media","id":"18639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18639"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/40181020-f485-4bdd-bd27-2314a782b7a8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/40181020-f485-4bdd-bd27-2314a782b7a8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":509,"height":477}},{"type":"media","id":"18640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18640"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2f631339-2e40-46b4-9c43-4ecb0405bf2f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2f631339-2e40-46b4-9c43-4ecb0405bf2f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":509,"height":477}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80396"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T18:49:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-09T18:49:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1881"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"